File: platform/cli/src/commands/audit.ts (lines 241-305) — the handleAudit function's try/catch for the server fetch.

The status command already has the correct pattern. In platform/cli/src/commands/status.ts:
- Lines 62-69: isNonOpenTabsHttpError() checks for 4xx (except 401) or non-JSON content type
- Lines 87-96: When isNonOpenTabsHttpError returns true, status prints 'No OpenTabs server found on port <N>. The port may be in use by another service.'

The audit command (audit.ts) currently handles HTTP errors at lines 255-261:
```
if (res.status === 401) { ... 'Authentication failed' ... }
if (!res.ok) { ... 'Error: MCP server returned HTTP ${res.status}.' ... }
```

Fix: Import isNonOpenTabsHttpError from status.ts (or extract it to a shared location if it's not already exported — check first). Add a check between the 401 handler and the generic !res.ok handler:
```
if (isNonOpenTabsHttpError(res.status, res.headers.get('content-type'))) {
  console.error(pc.red(`No OpenTabs server found on port ${port}.`));
  console.error(pc.dim('The port may be in use by another service.'));
  process.exit(1);
}
```

IMPORTANT: isNonOpenTabsHttpError is currently a local function in status.ts (not exported). You will need to either: (a) extract it to a shared utility (e.g., platform/cli/src/config.ts where isConnectionRefused already lives), or (b) export it from status.ts and import in audit.ts. Option (a) is cleaner — move it to config.ts alongside isConnectionRefused since both are error-classification helpers used across commands. Move the isTimeout helper too if it's also duplicated. Make sure to update the imports in status.ts after the move.
